Dereference remote objects with native code

Previously we rely on the v8util.setDestructor to dereference the remote
objects in JavaScript, however as documented in V8, it is forbidden to
call V8 APIs in object's destructor (e.g. the weak callback), and doing
so would result in crashs.

This commit removes the JavaScript setDestructor method, and avoids
doing the dereference work with V8.

lock in last known working jison dist files + buggy source files for future comparison as we continue working on the parser.
regenerated library files: all tests PASS once again...
regenerated library files (selectively, as there's still a glitch regarding the lexer options derived from the parser options, so we don't update all library files until that one is fixed)

don't backpatch lexer's yytext, yylineno or yyleng when it's not provided by the lexer already: keep the patching of the lexer instance to a bare minimum (that would be patching `lexer.yylloc` only now).

- fix corrupted console output/reports due to printf-style behaviour of console.log, console.warn, et al: https://nodejs.org/api/console.html#console_console_log_data_args
- updated NPM packages
- point NPM package as the 'scoped package' @gerhobbelt/nomnom as the original nomnom package is unmaintained for quite a while and we depend on the features in @gerhobbelt/nomnom anyway.
- add the CLI option `--export-AST` which exports the parsed grammar (and its lexer spec, when included) as JSON; this replaces the `jison2json` functionality: that little tool has been lagging behind for quite a while now.
- prepare for a `--prettier` output option, which pretty-prints the entire generated parser/lexer.
- fix error recovery related options now that we know whether we actually have any recovery rules at all: ensure all related error recovery options are disabled when error recovery is not available at all.
- regenerated library files using the updated modules.

- updated Makefile to properly patch the modules' library files while they get copied into lib/util/
- patched all `require()` statements in the examples as well to match the 'scoped package' dependencies listed in package.json. This is also related to https://github.com/GerHobbelt/jison/issues/11. Grmbkl!@#$%^&*!
- jison modules DO NOT belong in the **dependencies**, but should reside in the **devDependencies**. Where I screwed this up, I don't know (git blame should hand me the answer to that but I'll do that later when I feel like it), but now that we move towards 'scoped packages' it's biting me in the aXX!  :-(
- regenerated library files

- fixed `noMain` option default: TRUE --> DO **NOT** include `main()`-invoking code at the end of the generated file when you are producing CommonJS/etc. format sourcecode files for the parser.
- updated the codegen-feature-tester reference files
- bumped build revision
rebuilt library files and updated package file with default `build` task.

rebuilt jison library files (parsers): jison + jison-lex now use bleeding edge @gerhobbelt/recast::prettyPrint rather than @gerhobbelt/prettier: the former has several significant improvements around (trailing) comment placement and box comment formatting, resulting in much nicer output.

- fix https://github.com/GerHobbelt/jison/issues/19: `prettyPrintRange()` SHOULly receive yylloc argument(s); the 'lexer context' is already available via its `this`, which SHOULD be correct due to how you invoke this API everywhere: `this.prettyPrintRange(...)` or `yylexer.prettyPrintRange(...)`
- also fix `checkActionBlock()`: feed it the action code block's yylloc location info so that it can internally manipulate the code block so that the action code block **parse-as-JS-for-validation** operation will report some sane line numbers in its error reports.

lexer: unknown options, etc. should not come as array 0/1 indexed sets, but as key/value-pair objects instead for better code readability if we ever choose to access those bits of the parsed lexer/parser.
accept `%option` as an alias for `%options`; ditto for `%parse-param` vs. `%parse-params`
checking in at least some of the more-or-less reliable regenerated library files: I think the lexer is doing okay, but there's still quite a bit of work to be done in the EBNF parser...

- use updated XRegExp library with `isNative` fixes to generate code with fewer (if possible *none*) XRegExp references
- updated lexer grammar to support the new `%{{..%}}` etc constructs (`{...}` support is still buggy in the new grammar)
- fix lexer grammar for arrow actions. (Needs test cases)
regenerated library files; picked the approved ones while we continue work on the parser.

- WARNING: lexer.unput() also unputs=rewinds the `match`, `matches`, `matched` and `yytext` lexer member values. Sometimes you don't want `yytext` to change like that, in which case you must re-set it from a local copy you made just before calling unput()` :: see the lex and bnf lexer specs, which exhibit this behaviour
- fixed the 'regex patching' code in both lex.l and bnf.l (they're the same piece of code, anyway): check the regexes, not the rule ID# numbers *and* cache the patch in the lexer itself or the next call to parser.parse() may fail -- this behaviour was observed in the bnf unit tests.
- migrated another chunk of common code from lexer and bnf-parser to helpers lib.
- removed surplus lexer action rules as now `setupDelimitedActionChunkLexerRegex()` actually *works*, obsoleting those extra lexer rules.
- cleaned up the `ONLY_AN_ID_re` logic in the parser specs: anything that's guaranteed to be a single statement, i.e. has no semicolons at least and fits on a single line, is sure to work as-is when pasted at the end of a `return` statement: when it was buggy before, it will remain buggy; when it was good before, it'll remain the same after. That's one more XRegExp-special regex gone from the core.
- more work done on the refactoring of the BNF grammar and lexer specs: we're getting soemwhere, now that the initial bunch of unit tests almost pass! (1 failure; though we still have several test files and work stages to go before this is done and validated against at least a few basic grammars. Only then can we truly say there's a 0.6.5 release due...)

snapshot of work done thus far on lexer + ebnf parser: non-working. use for comparison with subsequent activity. Lexer unit tests pass almost all, but the showSource() interface is crap IMHO: it doesn't produce complete runnable code as the moduleInclude chunk is not included, etc. (I wonder why I hadn't bothered about it before,l but the the internal compile-test is whether the code *compiles* in Node/JavaScript, rather than testing whether it *executes*!

jison lexing: lexer rules' action code now gets gobbled up a little more aggressively when it's not in braces or `%{...%}` blocks: we consume any `|` pipe symbols in there as anything that would follow those would cause the lexer grammar to barf a hairball anyway as you cannot have regexes start in an indented position anyway.

refactor(ngModelController,formController): centralize and simplify logic

The previous logic for async validation in
`ngModelController` and `formController` was not maintainable:
- control logic is in multiple parts, e.g. `ctrl.$setValidity`
  waits for end of promises and continuous the control flow
  for async validation
- logic for updating the flags `ctrl.$error`, `ctrl.$pending`, `ctrl.$valid`
  is super complicated, especially in `formController`

This refactoring makes the following changes:
- simplify async validation: centralize control logic
  into one method in `ngModelController`:
  * remove counters `invalidCount` and `pendingCount`
  * use a flag `currentValidationRunId` to separate
    async validator runs from each other
  * use `$q.all` to determine when all async validators are done
- centralize way how `ctrl.$modelValue` and `ctrl.$invalidModelValue`
  is updated
- simplify `ngModelController/formCtrl.$setValidity` and merge
  `$$setPending/$$clearControlValidity/$$clearValidity/$$clearPending`
  into one method, that is used by `ngModelController` AND
  `formController`
  * remove diff calculation, always calculate the correct state anew,
    only cache the css classes that have been set to not
    trigger too many css animations.
  * remove fields from `ctrl.$error` that are valid and add private `ctrl.$$success`:
    allows to correctly separate states for valid, invalid, skipped and pending,
    especially transitively across parent forms.
- fix bug in `ngModelController`:
  * only read out `input.validity.badInput`, but not
    `input.validity.typeMismatch`,
    to determine parser error: We still want our `email`
    validator to run event when the model is validated.
- fix bugs in tests that were found as the logic is now consistent between
  `ngModelController` and `formController`

BREAKING CHANGE:
- `ctrl.$error` does no more contain entries for validators that were
  successful.
- `ctrl.$setValidity` now differentiates between `true`, `false`,
  `undefined` and `null`, instead of previously only truthy vs falsy.

Closes #8941

Added tablesorter-2.22.1 side by side with the existing one
and did some prep work on FannieReportPage to use the newer
tablesorter. Prep work is still commented out. Issues I see
in switching to the newer tablesorter w/ bootstrap theme:
* Up/down glyphicons do not appear is column headers. Unclear why.
* The sorted column is not highlighted separately from other headers
* Overall text size is larger. Possibly nice for viewing but less
  ideal for printing.
* Paths change between versions. May need to restructure 2.22.1
  so a simple symlink switch between versions won't break non-report
  pages that use tablesorter.
* Reports need print CSS. May help with the text-size issue.
